results.description:
Imagine that you have put your winter coat away early and can't find it during a sudden onset of spring frost or that you cannot take that insulated coat off in the first place and overheat. 
We are collecting photographs of mountain goats across time and space to evaluate their winter coat shedding. We will be relating the phenology (timing) of their molt to thermal change. Old photographs, scanned from slides and film, are especially important to address this question but the date and location information is crucial. Photographs from mountain goats' native and introduced range will be evaluated.  
In addition to this space on iNat, we are accepting photo submissions via our project web portal (where photos will be publicly visible and under a creative commons license) here: https://www.citsci.org/CWIS438/Browse/Project/Project_Info.php?ProjectID=2045
We are asking iNaturalists to please upload their photos to our CitSci web portal to express their permission to participate in this project, or otherwise to add your photos to our project on iNat: https://www.inaturalist.org/projects/mountain-goat-molt-project-add-your-photos 
Contributors of photos will be acknowledged in project outputs. 
Please share your mountain goat photographs to help us understand how they are responding to a warming climate.
Thank you for your help and interest in this project! 
Dr. Kate Nowak & the Mountain Goat Molt Project Team
results.title: Mountain Goat Molt Project - Shows All iNat Observations

results.description:
Help Ontario Parks measure and protect our province’s amazing biodiversity! Every observation counts and anyone can participate. 
Our provincial parks collectively protect over 10% of Ontario. A biodiverse Ontario includes everything from midges to moose and water striders to white pines. What will you see? 

Rare species are hidden to protect them. Please join the ‘Rare Species of Ontario (NHIC)’ project and your Species at Risk sightings will be counted: http://inaturalist.ca/projects/nhic-rare-species-of-ontario 
Learn more about Ontario’s Provincial Parks at https://www.ontarioparks.com/
results.title: Ontario Parks

results.description: BioBlitz Canada 150 was coordinated by the Canadian Wildlife Federation and partners in conservation and funded by the Government of Canada as one of 38 Canada150 Signature Projects. Using iNaturalist Canada as the official platform, species observations were recorded at 35 events across the country that brought together the Canadian public with scientists to explore and inventory the richness of Canada’s biodiversity. Click on the “See Results” tab for an overview of what was found (you may need to adjust the window size to see the entire page). And discover more stories of Canada’s “nature selfie” at bioblitzcanada.ca. You can still be a part of BioBlitz Canada 150 by helping to identify species listed here in this project. You can continue to bioblitz all year round by adding your wildlife observations to iNaturalist.ca. If you haven’t already, download the free iNaturalist Canada app and you can help contribute to this ongoing data base. BioBlitz Canada 150, un des 38 projets Signature Canada 150, était coordonné par la Fédération canadienne de la faune et financé par le gouvernement du Canada. Avec l’aide d’iNaturalist Canada, les observations furent enregistrées lors des 35 événements partout au pays, pendant lesquels les Canadiens se sont joints aux scientifiques pour explorer et inventorier les richesses de la biodiversité du Canada. Cliquez sur « Voir résultats » pour un aperçu des espèces recensées. (Vous allez peut-être devoir réduire la grosseur de l’image pour voir la page au complet.) Visitez bioblitzcanada.ca pour en savoir plus sur « l’égoportrait de la nature » du Canada. Vous pouvez toujours faire partie de BioBlitz Canada 150 en aidant à identifier les espèces répertoriées dans ce projet. Vous pouvez également participer à des bioblitz à longueur d’année en ajoutant des observations sur iNaturalist.ca. Si ce n’est pas déjà fait, téléchargez l’appli gratuite iNaturalist Canada et contribuez à cette base de données perpétuelle.
results.title: BioBlitz Canada 150

results.description:
The goal of this project is to collect observations of caterpillars from Eastern North America. Please help us by annotating caterpillar observations Life Stage = Larva. I hope that this project will eventually become something of a go-to source for caterpillar information, with a repository of photos and locations, and that it will attract a group of members who are interested in observing caterpillars & helping with caterpillar identification.

For this project, Eastern North America is defined as all parts of Canada, the United States, and Mexico that are east of the 100th meridian.
results.title: Caterpillars of Eastern North America

results.description:
The City Nature Challenge is an international effort for people to find and document plants and wildlife in cities across the globe. It’s a bioblitz-style competition where cities are in a contest against each other to see who can make the most observations of nature, who can find the most species, and who can engage the most people. In 2018, 69 cities around the world are taking part in the City Nature Challenge - check below to see if your city is taking part, track what is being found, and see who is in the lead!

There is nature all around us, even in our cities! Knowing what species are in our city and where they are helps us study and protect them, but the ONLY way to do that is by all of us - scientists, land managers, and the community - working together to find and document the nature in our area. By participating in the City Nature Challenge, not only do you learn more about your local nature, but you can also make your city a better place - for you and other species!

The City Nature Challenge is organized by the citizen science teams at the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County and the California Academy of Sciences.
results.title: City Nature Challenge 2018
